# State Management Standard

## Purpose

This rule defines where state lives in the Next.js frontend and how to manage it without duplicating backend truth or creating inconsistent UI.

State must have a single owner. Never synchronize the same data in multiple places without a clear strategy.

---

# Scope

Covers:

- Server state (FastAPI data in Server Components)
- URL state (search params, route segments)
- Client ephemeral state (Zustand)
- Form state (React Hook Form — see `frontend/04-forms`)
- Cache and revalidation (Next.js fetch cache)

Does not cover backend session storage or database state.

---

# State Ownership Matrix

| State type | Owner | Mechanism | Example |
|------------|-------|-----------|---------|
| Remote authoritative data | Server / API | Server Component fetch | Product catalog |
| User session | Backend + cookie | Server Component reads cookie | Auth status |
| URL-driven UI | URL | `searchParams`, `useRouter` | Filters, pagination |
| Cross-page client UI | Client | Zustand | Cart drawer open |
| Form in progress | Client | React Hook Form | Checkout address |
| Optimistic UI | Client + server reconcile | Zustand + mutation response | Cart quantity |

When unsure, prefer server ownership. Move to client only with justification.

---

# Server State

Fetch in Server Components from FastAPI.

Rules:

- Treat API responses as read-only in Server Components
- Use `cache()` from React for deduplicated reads within a request
- Configure revalidation explicitly (`next: { revalidate: 60 }` or tags)
- Pass serializable snapshots to Client Components as props
- Do not pass class instances, functions, or Dates without serialization

Pattern:

```tsx
// app/products/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { getProducts } from "@/lib/api/catalog";

export default async function ProductsPage() {
  const products = await getProducts();
  return <ProductGrid products={products} />;
}
```

Invalidate server cache after mutations via `revalidatePath`, `revalidateTag`, or Server Actions.

---

# URL State

Use URL search params for shareable, bookmarkable UI state.

Good for:

- Pagination (`?page=2`)
- Sort order (`?sort=price-asc`)
- Facet filters (`?category=shoes&size=42`)
- Tab selection when shareable

Implement in Server Components by reading `searchParams` prop; update via `<Link>` or `router.push` preserving other params.

Avoid mirroring URL state into Zustand. The URL is the source of truth.

---

# Client State with Zustand

Use Zustand for client-only state that:

- Spans multiple Client Components
- Must persist across navigations within the session (cart, UI chrome)
- Is not authoritative (backend still validates on submit)

Store location: `apps/web/src/store/`

---

# Zustand Store Structure

Always use `subscribeWithSelector` middleware.

Separate state and actions interfaces:

```typescript
import { create } from "zustand";
import { subscribeWithSelector } from "zustand/middleware";

interface CartState {
  items: CartItem[];
  isOpen: boolean;
}

interface CartActions {
  addItem: (item: CartItem) => void;
  removeItem: (id: string) => void;
  setOpen: (open: boolean) => void;
}

type CartStore = CartState & CartActions;

export const useCartStore = create<CartStore>()(
  subscribeWithSelector((set, get) => ({
    items: [],
    isOpen: false,
    addItem: (item) =>
      set((state) => ({
        items: [...state.items.filter((i) => i.id !== item.id), item],
      })),
    removeItem: (id) =>
      set((state) => ({ items: state.items.filter((i) => i.id !== id) })),
    setOpen: (open) => set({ isOpen: open }),
  }))
);
```

Export stores from `apps/web/src/store/index.ts`.

---

# Zustand Selector Rules

Use atomic selectors to minimize re-renders:

```typescript
// Good
const items = useCartStore((s) => s.items);

// Avoid — re-renders on any store change
const { items, isOpen } = useCartStore();
```

For derived data, use selectors or memoized helpers outside the store when expensive.

---

# Cart and Checkout State

The cart is a special case:

- Optimistic UI may live in Zustand for instant feedback
- Server cart (FastAPI) is authoritative at checkout
- On checkout submit, send cart to API; handle conflicts (price change, stock) with server response
- Clear client cart only after confirmed order creation

Never store payment card data in Zustand or any client store.

---

# React Context

Use React Context sparingly.

Acceptable for:

- Theme provider (shadcn/next-themes)
- Narrow feature-scoped dependency injection

Do not use Context as a global application store. Use Zustand instead for app-wide client state.

---

# Server Actions vs Client Mutations

Prefer Server Actions when:

- Mutation should revalidate server cache
- No optimistic UI is required
- Credentials stay server-side

Use client fetch + Zustand when:

- Optimistic updates improve perceived performance
- Real-time feedback is critical (cart badge)

Always reconcile optimistic state with API response errors.

---

# Persistence

Default: Zustand stores are in-memory only.

If persisting to `localStorage` (e.g., cart guest session):

- Use `persist` middleware with a versioned schema
- Never persist auth tokens or PII beyond what GDPR/policy allows
- Hydration must handle SSR mismatch (`skipHydration` or client-only mount)

---

# Synchronization Anti-Patterns

Never:

- Copy full product catalog into Zustand
- Store user profile in Zustand when Server Components can refetch
- Dual-write the same field to URL and Zustand
- Use `useEffect` to sync props into global store on every render
- Treat client cart as source of truth through payment

---

# Decision Rules

Ask:

Is this data from FastAPI?

Yes → Server state unless optimistic UI requires a client copy.

Should the user share this view via URL?

Yes → URL state.

Is this UI-only and ephemeral?

Yes → Local `useState` or Zustand if shared.

Does it survive navigation?

Yes → Zustand or URL, not `useState` in a leaf.

---

# Validation Checklist

- Single source of truth identified
- No duplicated API data in global client store
- Zustand selectors are atomic
- Store files in `src/store/` with tests
- Server cache invalidation defined for mutations
- No secrets or card data in client stores

